Email Question: Does HubSpot now auto-inject vcode now into emails to work with outlook? One of our templates have been causing issues in other browsers recently, and now we've removed the vcode and outlook looks good... cc: <@U504BHZ6K>
out of curiosity was a it a templated email or the new drag n droppy emails they have?
templated email
I haven’t noticed in templated emails them injecting vcode. but wouldn’t be surprised if they started doing it on CTAs one day.
what is vcode?
outlook specific code for templates

It’s technically called VML

so fun history lesson about HTML emails and Outlook incoming

Outlook at one point used the internet explorer rendering engine to render emails, things were okay but not awesome in HTML email land.

Then the outlook team decided “hey Microsoft Word already has formatting controls and can output html. Why don’t we use Word as the rendering engine instead?

So they made the switch. Microsoft Word supports VML(Vector Markup Language), The word rendering engine however does not support a lot of CSS properly. 

So clever dev’s have for years been faking css features using VML which will only render in outlook.

So often when you look at tutorials for HTML emails you’ll see things like bulletproof buttons(which use VML) background images(use VML) etc.
AH
To this day the Outlook desktop client is still an aweful POS but we have to support it because big corporations buy into the microsoft ecosystem
I appreciate the background. I didn't know they did that with word

Yea, the word rendering engine causes most of Outlooks issues. For example this fun one I discovered once - if you have a single image that is taller than like 1400px you’ll find that in outlook it renders cut in half with a huge 2000px or so gap in between the halves.

Guess why that happens - here’s a hint, it’s because of Microsoft Word and has nothing to do with the web.












That size image is larger than 1 physical page in Microsoft Word, therefore the image is split onto two pages. In Outlook it causes a gigantic space where the paper’s margins would be.
lol that's an edge case
Who is designing emails that are one image that is 1400 pixels tall
Microsoft Employee - “That’s a feature!”

the number might be less than 1400px I just remember it was pretty tall.  The reason was a design reason, it was like a bunch of photos that didn’t have text and didn’t make sense to separate into their own cells.
I gotcha
I had spent like 5 hours trying to solve that one, and when I figured it out I literally burst out laughing and couldn’t believe it.
oh man
That is usually ready to cut someone time

haha yea I was about that flustered. there were several posts online about it but most people had no idea why and no solution. 

Solution fortunately was really easy, you just cut the image in half and since neither image is larger than 1 page you were fine. real obscure.

went through all 5 stages of grief lol
<@U7SL518D6> That is a super interesting tidbit of info. I knew emails rendered horribly in Outlook but not why!

*Maybe a Stupid Question*
This morning I create a basic conversion Path
LP with a Calculated Form > Thank You Page with Contact Token (firstname and calculated result) 

When I made some tests I discovered that Personalized Tokens didn’t appear on the page !

HubSpot support told me that datas do not have time to be stored between my LP and my TYP

*Anyone has a tips to show Personalized Tokens on Thank you page after form submission ?*

You can submit the form silently and then do a setTimeout in the HubSpot embed code, or you can setup the confirmation page to do a timeout on the page for 100 second then redirects you to the proper confirmation page
basically you just need to give HubSpot another few moments to process the data before you load the page

Another possibly easier option would be to just use a service like bitly or something. It would fragment your analytics though.

since it’s not cross-origin, (I think I mentioned this in another hypothetical thread somewhere as well) you can probably even manipulate the contents of the iframe / trigger off actions in the PDF… though I have NO idea how that would function in practice, and it probably belongs in the <#CBA9UA4EN|javascript> thread)
